narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: A deep appreciation for Rabbinic humor
I developed so much new knowledge regarding humor in rabbinical literature, most importantly, that it all revolves around playfulness and the power that play encompasses.
This course synthesized the Ancient world, Rabbinic literature, and modern theories of comedy and play.  It was a gift and a joy to participate.
I was able to develop insights to read rabbinic literature juxtaposed with Greco-Roman Literature, and closely analyze rabbinic literature, especially through the lens of Humor and Play.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: It was only strong. Seriously, Professor Hayes is brilliant and brings more energy and love to each of her classes than I have ever witnessed a professor do before.
The course could not have been stronger. A+!

One of the strengths of this course was putting conversation rabbinic literature, Greco-Roman literature and Christian texts all together, and examine how similar/different they are. This helps to broaden students perspectives and shed new light on interpreting texts.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I would definitely recommend this course to another student because anyone who gets to take a class with Professor Hayes is extremely lucky.
Yes! YES! But alas this is the only year it will be taught.
This course was the most extraordinary course I completed at Yale. I recommend it to everyone.

Yes, this class was insightful, informative and helpful to read rabbinic literature closely, through the theories of Humor and Play. This course will help other students to be equipped with skills to examine rabbinic literature juxtapose with other (contemporary) texts.
